    earlier we noticed that if you give `0` as argument for ./level09 it gives`0`
    if input `01` ouput is `02` and so on
    same with `1` which gives `1` and `11` gives `12`
    So:
    convert token to hexa, substract to each character its index value
    which gives:
        `66 34 6b 6d 6d 36 70 7c 3d 82 7f 70 82 6e 83 82 44 42 83 44 75 7b 7f 8c 89 0a`

    Little bash script that does it all for us (ngl, we did it by hand the first time)
```
    #!/bin/bash

    line=$(cat ~/token)
    
    for ((i=0; i<${#line}; i++)); do
        char="${line:$i:1}";
        ascii=$(LC_ALL=C printf "%d" "'$char");
        (( ascii -= i ));
        new_char=$(LC_ALL=C awk "BEGIN{printf \"%c\", $ascii}");
        echo -n "$new_char";
        done;
    echo;
```

    LC_ALL=C tells bash and awk to treat all bytes as raw single bytes, not UTF-8.
